1. To run all the tests in terminal - py.test -v -s
where -v stands for verbose(more information) -s(output log/message)

2. To run tests with specific names(group wise/module wise)- py.test -k (nameofthetestcase)-v -s
example-py.test -k greetings -s

3. To run a specific test file- py.test test_1.py -s -->make sure you are under the directory

4. if you only want to execute/skip a particular test case from a file use @pytest.mark.smoke-- only execute the test where you mentioned it
example- @pytest.mark.smoke
def test_testcase1():
    print("testcase1")
to skip- @pytest.mark.skip
def test_testcase1():
    print("testcase1")

5. xFail- where the test is expected to fail
if the test fails it will print xFAIL
AND if the test somehow passed then it will return xPass

6. Fixture- can be used in many forms

1. to use as setup and teardown methods after each tests run or it can be applied as a class level as well
2. if the fixture is only needed in a specific test case then it can be created in the same test file otherwise we can create a separate file called
"conftest" to declare the fixture and use it in every test files

to open allure report- allure open allure-report